# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-machine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-machine/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-machine/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-machine/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-machine/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-machine/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-machine/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy, a fundamental distinction exists between **abstract** and **concrete** entities.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] While there is no universally accepted definition, common examples illustrate the difference: numbers, sets, and ideas are typically classified as abstract objects, whereas plants, dogs, and planets are considered concrete objects.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] *Causal influence* – Concrete objects can cause and be affected by other entities (e.g., a rock breaking a window), whereas abstract objects (e.g., the number 2) lack causal powers and do not cause anything to happen in the physical world.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] *Metaphysical relation* – In metaphysics, concrete objects are specific, individual things (particulars), while abstract objects represent general concepts or categories (universals).
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] *Ontological domain* – Concrete objects belong to the physical realm (or both the physical and mental realms), whereas abstract objects belong to neither.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Another view is that it is the distinction between contingent existence versus necessary existence; however, philosophers differ on which type of existence here defines abstractness, as opposed to concreteness.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Despite this diversity of views, there is broad agreement concerning most objects as to whether they are abstract or concrete, such that most interpretations agree, for example, that rocks are concrete objects while numbers are abstract objects.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects are most commonly used in philosophy, particularly metaphysics, and semantics.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] They are sometimes called ***abstracta*** in contrast to ***concreta***.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] The term *abstract object* is said to have been coined by Willard Van Orman Quine.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract object theory is a discipline that studies the nature and role of abstract objects.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] It holds that properties can be related to objects in two ways: through exemplification and through encoding.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete objects exemplify their properties while abstract objects merely encode them.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] This approach is also known as the dual copula strategy.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] The type–token distinction identifies physical objects that are tokens of a particular type of thing.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] The "type" of which it is a part is in itself an abstract object.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects have often garnered the interest of philosophers because they raise problems for popular theories.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In ontology, abstract objects are considered problematic for physicalism and some forms of naturalism.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Historically, the most important ontological dispute about abstract objects has been the problem of universals.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In epistemology, abstract objects are considered problematic for empiricism.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] If abstracta lack causal powers and spatial location, how do we know about them?
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] It is hard to say how they can affect our sensory experiences, and yet we seem to agree on a wide range of claims about them.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy of religion, the existence of abstract objects is sometimes considered a problem for divine aseity, which, for example, prompted the Christian philosopher William Lane Craig to argue against uncreated abstract objects.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Other Christian philosophers, such as Peter van Inwagen, have conversely argued *for* their existence, seeing no conflict between them and theism.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Some, such as Ernst Mally, Edward Zalta and arguably, Plato in his Theory of Forms, have held that abstract objects constitute the defining subject matter of metaphysics or philosophical inquiry more broadly.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] To the extent that philosophy is independent of empirical research, and to the extent that empirical questions do not inform questions about abstracta, philosophy would seem especially suited to answering these latter questions.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In modern philosophy, the distinction between abstract and concrete was explored by Immanuel Kant and G.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Gottlob Frege said that abstract objects, such as propositions, were members of a third realm, different from the external world or from internal consciousness.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Another popular proposal for drawing the abstract–concrete distinction contends that an object is abstract if it lacks causal power.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] A causal power has the ability to affect something causally.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Thus, the empty set is abstract because it cannot act on other objects.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] One problem with this view is that it is not clear exactly what it is to have causal power.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] For a more detailed exploration of the abstract–concrete distinction, see the relevant *Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy* article.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] In the 2010s, there was some philosophical interest in the development of a third category of objects known as the **quasi-abstract**.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Quasi-abstract objects have drawn particular attention in the area of social ontology and documentality.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Specifically, the ability to have temporal location, but not spatial location, and have causal agency (if only by acting through representatives).
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] These characteristics are exhibited by a number of social objects, including states of the international legal system.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Jean Piaget uses the terms "concrete" and "formal" to describe two different types of learning.
[src:animal-machine/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete thinking involves facts and descriptions about everyday, tangible objects, while abstract (formal operational) thinking involves a mental process.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes developed this view against the Aristotelian and Scholastic tradition, which explained life in terms of soul and final causes.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] His account became a well-known part of Cartesian natural philosophy and drew criticism from later philosophers and writers, especially on the question of animal sensation and suffering.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes rejected the view that living beings act for intrinsic ends.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Instead, he held that bodily processes could be explained through the motion and interaction of matter.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] On this basis, he treated animal life as a matter of mechanism rather than soul.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Brown, Descartes had developed the doctrine of animal automatism by 1619 and continued to defend it throughout his life, including in his correspondence with Henry More in the late 1640s.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes compared animals to hydraulic automata, such as the moving statues in the gardens at Saint-Germain-en-Laye.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] He described the animal body as a system of nerves, muscles, and *animal spirits* operating by purely physical means.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] On this account, sensation and movement in animals did not require thought or reason.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] He also proposed two tests that, in his view, distinguished humans from animals.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] The first was the capacity for genuine language, meaning the ability to produce new and meaningful speech.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] The second was the ability to act with general adaptability across different situations.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes held that animals failed both tests.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Their sounds and actions, however complex, were taken to be the products of bodily organisation rather than understanding.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes held that only humans possess immortal, immaterial souls created directly by God.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Animals, by contrast, were explained in terms of bodily structure and the movement of animal spirits.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] This view marked a sharp distinction between humans and other animals within Cartesian philosophy.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] At the same time, Descartes acknowledged similarities between human and animal bodies, including shared organs and physiological processes.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] He also allowed that animals could acquire habits and show some flexibility in behaviour, but he treated these as mechanical changes in bodily arrangement rather than as evidence of thought.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Descartes' account of animals was criticised during his lifetime and afterwards.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Brown identifies critics including Pierre Gassendi, Nicolas Malebranche, and the Cambridge Platonists.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Ralph Cudworth, for example, argued that animals possess a kind of soul marked by self-activity and sensibility, and so should not be treated as equivalent to inanimate matter.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Brown also notes that practices such as animal trials in premodern Europe suggest that animals were often treated as beings capable of agency and responsibility, which stood at odds with Descartes' account.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Opposition to the doctrine also appeared in religious writing.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In the 1760 sermon *Universal Charity*, the preacher rejected the view that animals are "mere Machines and Pieces of Clock-work, without Sense, Perception, or Consciousness".
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In the 18th century, Julien Offray de La Mettrie extended the machine analogy to humans.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In *L'Homme Machine* ("Man a Machine"; 1747), he rejected Cartesian dualism and argued that thought and consciousness arise from bodily organisation.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In modern animal ethics, Descartes has often been criticised for denying animal consciousness or sentience.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In *Animal Liberation* (1975), Peter Singer called Descartes' position the "absolute nadir" of Western thought about animals.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Tom Regan also discussed Descartes critically in *The Case for Animal Rights* (1983).
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Anita Guerrini notes that in 1982 a member of the Animal Liberation Front defaced a portrait of Descartes at the Royal Society in protest.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] In 1978, John Cottingham argued that Descartes may not have denied all forms of animal sensation.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] Cottingham distinguished between *cogitatio* ("thought") and *sensus* ("sensation"), and pointed to passages in which Descartes described animals as expressing fear, hunger, and anger.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] He concluded that Descartes' position on animal feeling was less straightforward than later summaries often suggest.
[src:animal-machine/animal-machine] The doctrine of the animal machine continues to appear in discussions of animal consciousness, the moral status of animals, and the history of theories of mind and mechanism.
